'''Arvydas Romas Sabonis''' (born December 19, 1964) is a retired [[Lithuania]]n [[professional]] [[basketball]] player and a businessman. He played the [[center (basketball)|center]] position.

==Early years==
Sabonis first began playing basketball at age 13. By the time he was 15 years old he was a member of the Soviet national junior team.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/playerfile/arvydas_sabonis/bio.html Arvydas Sabonis Bio]</ref>

==Pro career==
Sabonis made his pro debut in 1981 with the [[BC <U+017D>algiris|<U+017D>algiris]] of his hometown [[Kaunas]] where he won three consecutive Soviet League titles and reached the 1986 [[Euroleague]] finals.

Sabonis was selected by the [[Atlanta Hawks]] with the 77th pick of the [[1985 NBA Draft]]. However, the selection was voided because Sabonis was under 21 at the time of the draft. The following spring, he suffered a devastating [[Achilles' tendon]] injury. Nevertheless, he was selected by the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] with the 24th pick of the [[1986 NBA Draft]].

Sabonis wasn't allowed to play in the NBA by Soviet authorities until 1989. However, he did come to [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]] for rehabilitate his injury with Blazers trainers. He also practiced with the team.

In the 1988 [[Summer Olympics]], Sabonis led the [[Soviet Union national basketball team|Soviet Union]] to a gold medal win through an [[United States national basketball team|United States]] team that featured future NBA All-Stars [[David Robinson]], [[Mitch Richmond]] and [[Danny Manning]] in the semi-finals, and eventually beating [[Yugoslavia national basketball team|Yugoslavia]] in the finals.

In 1992, after playing with the the [[CB Valladolid]] for three seasons, Sabonis joined the [[Real Madrid Baloncesto|Real Madrid]] and won two [[Liga ACB|Spanish League]] titles and an [[Euroleague]] title in 1995. During the 1994-95 regular season with Real Madrid, he averaged 22.8 points, 13.2 rebounds, 2.6 blocked shots, and 2.4 assists per game.

In 1995, Sabonis signed with the Blazers. He had a successful rookie campaign, averaging 14.5 points on 55% shooting and 8.1 rebounds. Sabonis was selected to the All-Rookie First Team and was runner-up in both [[NBA Rookie of the Year Award|Rookie of the Year]] and [[NBA Sixth Man of the Year Award|Sixth Man of the Year]] votings. His postseason averages were up to 23.6 points and 10.2 rebounds.

Sabonis averaged 16.0 points, 10.0 rebounds and 3.0 assists in 1997-98, all career-highs.

He won the [[Euroscar Award|European Player of the Year]] twice while playing with the Blazers. He also became a fan favorite.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/blazers/special_features/Portland_will_miss_Arvydas_Sab-84264-41.html Portland Will Miss Arvydas Sabonis]</ref>

The question that surrounds Sabonis' NBA career revolve around how good could he have been had he played in the NBA during his prime.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?page=Euro-Sabonis Best of the Euroleague and NBA: Arvydas Sabonis]</ref><ref>[http://probasketball.about.com/od/internationalbasketball/a/08olyarvydassab.htm 2008 Olympics - Basketball - Where Are They Now? Arvydas Sabonis]</ref> Sabonis was over 31 when he joined the Blazers, by which time he had already won multiple gold medals and suffered through numerous injuries.

Sabonis came back to [[BC <U+017D>algiris|<U+017D>algiris]] to play his final season. He led the team to the Top 16 stage of the season and was named the Regular Season MVP and the Top 16 MVP. He also became the team's president.<ref>[http://www.euroleague.net/history/50-years/the-archive/i/26224/1609/item 50 Greatest contributors list: Arvydas Sabonis]</ref>

==Personal life==
Sabonis is married to Ingrida, a former Miss [[Vilnius]], fashion model and movie actress. Their son, Tautvydas, plays for the [[CB M<U+00E1>laga]] junior team.<ref>[http://www.euroleague.net/competition/players/showplayer?seasoncode=JT08&gamecode=81&pcode=001631 Tautvydas Sabonis 2008-09 Statistics]</ref>

